As a student:
    1) I want a clear, branded homepage that serves as the entry point to event discovery, making it easy to start searching and browsing.
    2) I want to easily browse all published events and use search and filter tools so I can quickly find activities that interest me.
    3) I want a clear button to claim my ticket, and if the event is paid, I need to be directed to a payment method placeholder.
    4) after claiming a ticket, I want to immediately see a digital ticket with a unique QR code so I can use it for check-in at the even
    5) I want a clear button on the event details page to easily add the event to my preferred digital calendar
As a user:
    6) I want the student-facing website to look and function perfectly so I can use it easily while on the go.

TASK BREAKDOWN FOR EACH USER STORY:
User Story 1:    
    Implement JavaScript logic to fetch data from API and handle client-side filtering (date, category, organization) to update the event card grid.
    Build the initial HTML structure and custom CSS for the student-facing homepage, including the persistent navigation and responsive base layout.
User Story 2: 
    Create a secure Python API endpoint that securely retrieves only those events marked status='current' (which means approved by admin) for public view.
    Create the basic HTML structure and custom CSS for the student-facing event listing page, that students will see with a responsive card grid and filter sidebar layout.
    Implement JavaScript logic that pulls data from the API, providing for client-side filtering for date, category, and organization to update the event card grid.
User Story 3: 
    Create a Python API endpoint to record a ticket claim in the database. Must handle both free claims and payment integration logic (placeholder redirect).
    Implement the JS logic to handle the "Claim Ticket" button click, managing the POST request for free claims and the redirect flow for paid events.
User Story 4: 
    Implement Python logic to generate a unique, secure ticket ID upon claim and provide the corresponding QR code data/image endpoint for the frontend to fetch.
    Implement the ticket view page (HTML/CSS) and JS to fetch and display the unique ticket details along with the generated QR code image after a successful claim.
User Story 5: 
    Implement a "Save to Calendar" button that uses client-side JavaScript to construct the necessary link
User Story 6: 
    Perform comprehensive testing on the student view for mobile responsiveness, filter stability, and overall user experience across major web browsers and phone devices.
